What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183412 trips in our dataset, we have 4646 unique bikes and the data is collected for Feb2019, we have 329 unique stations and we have 197 trip with no station name or id (maybe the user did not leave it in a station or the bike may had been broken or stolen!)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interesting to know the stations with no bike at all in certain times of a day because it means easy profit we miss.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

our main interest is the time of the day so I will use start_time, end_time, start_id, end_id, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year , member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip

I want to investigate more those 197 trip with no stattion id :

As we could see the distribution is extremely skewed to right means that most trips has short durations (75% of trips has a duration less than 1000 sec = (16min and 40sec) as we could see from describe method). def freq_poly(x, bins = 10, **kwargs):
    """ Custom frequency polygon / line plot code. """
    # set bin edges if none or int specified
    if type(bins) == int:
        bins = np.linspace(x.min(), x.max(), bins+1)
    bin_centers = (bin_edges[1:] + bin_edges[:-1]) / 2

    # compute counts
    data_bins = pd.cut(x, bins, right = False,
                       include_lowest = True)
    counts = x.groupby(data_bins).count()

    # create plot
    plt.errorbar(x = bin_centers, y = counts, **kwargs)

bin_edges = np.arange(0, 24+1, 1)

def in_out_list(station):
    ids =[]
    in_bikes = 0
    out_bikes = 0
    ids_final = []
    for bike in station[::-1]:
        ids.append(bike)
    ids_clear = [id_ for id_ in ids if str(id_) != 'nan']
    for bike in ids_clear[::-1]:
        if bike[2:] not in ids_final:
            ids_final.append(bike[2:])
            if bike[0] == 'f':
                in_bikes += 1
            else:
                out_bikes +=1
    return ids_clear

12 rows × 329 columns

The last trip reached between 8:00am and 9:00am so we will have 9 aditional rows. I will extract the out bikes number from each value and sum up for each row to get the number of bikes that in use in that time. Is not beautiful?

The above table shows the count of trips per station by end of the day

These are the number of trips ended in each station by the end of the day. There is two things must be considered, first we must exclude the bikes that started a new trip after the last end time in that day (a bike may start in a day and end in the following day) and the second thing we must consider is the same bike may have the same end station multiple times during the day so we must count the unique bike ids. we should also include another column for the count of bikes outside the stations.
